58b.title: Logical decision theories
58b.clickbait: Root page for topics on logical decision theory, with multiple intros for different audiences.
58b.text:
"Logical decision theories" are algorithms for making choices which embody some variant of "Decide as though you determine the logical output of your decision algorithm."

Besides the intros in the tabs above, [https://arxiv.org/abs/1710.05060 a formal paper on the "functional decision theory" variant of LDT is now available].  This is the best current introduction for those who prefer to read papers.

58d.title: Guide to Logical Decision Theory
58d.clickbait: The entry point for learning about logical decision theory.

58f.title: Introduction to Logical Decision Theory for Economists
58f.clickbait: An introduction to 'logical decision theory' and its implications for the Ultimatum Game, voting in elections, bargaining problems, and more.

5b2.title: Omega (alien philosopher-troll)
5b2.clickbait: The entity that sets up all those trolley problems.  An alien philosopher/troll imbued with unlimited powers, excellent predictive ability, and very odd motives.

5d6.title: Introduction to Logical Decision Theory for Computer Scientists
5d6.clickbait: 'Logical decision theory' from a math/programming standpoint, including how two agents with mutual knowledge of each other's code can cooperate on the Prisoner's Dilemma.

5gc.title: Introduction to Logical Decision Theory for Analytic Philosophers
5gc.clickbait: Why "choose as if controlling the logical output of your decision algorithm" is the most appealing candidate for the principle of rational choice.

5hp.title: 99LDT x 1CDT oneshot PD tournament as arguable counterexample to LDT doing better than CDT
5hp.clickbait: Arguendo, if 99 LDT agents and 1 CDT agent are facing off in a one-shot Prisoner's Dilemma tournament, the CDT agent does better on a problem that CDT considers 'fair'.

5kv.title: An Introduction to Logical Decision Theory for Everyone Else
5kv.clickbait: So like what the heck is 'logical decision theory' in terms a normal person can understand?

5pt.title: Newcomblike decision problems
5pt.clickbait: Decision problems in which your choice correlates with something other than its physical consequences (say, because somebody has predicted you very well) can do weird things to some decision theories.

5qn.title: Death in Damascus
5qn.clickbait: Death tells you that It is coming for you tomorrow.  You can stay in Damascus or flee to Aleppo.  Whichever decision you actually make is the wrong one.  This gives some decision theories trouble.

5rf.title: Toxoplasmosis dilemma
5rf.clickbait: A parasitic infection, carried by cats, may make humans enjoy petting cats more.  A kitten, now in front of you, isn't infected.  But if you *want* to pet it, you may already be infected.  Do you?

5rz.title: Updateless decision theories
5rz.clickbait: Decision theories that maximize their policies (mappings from sense inputs to actions), rather than using their sense inputs to update their beliefs and then selecting actions.

5s0.title: Parfit's Hitchhiker
5s0.clickbait: You are dying in the desert.  A truck-driver who is very good at reading faces finds you, and offers to drive you into the city if you promise to pay $1,000 on arrival.  You are a selfish rationalist.

5tp.title: Ultimatum Game
5tp.clickbait: A Proposer decides how to split $10 between themselves and the Responder.  The Responder can take what is offered, or refuse, in which case both parties get nothing.
